  "prompt_text": "Explain how a hash table works, including collision resolution strategies.",
  "response_text": "To explain how a hash table works and include collision resolution strategies:\n\nHash tables are data structures that store keys and values using a hash function to map keys to indices within an array called buckets. The key is hashed into a number between 0 and n-1, where n is the size of the bucket.\n\nWhen a new key-value pair is added to the hash table, the hash function calculates the index for the key based on its hash value. If there's no conflict (i.e., multiple keys have the same hash value), the key-value pair is stored directly in the corresponding bucket. However, if there's a collision (i.e., two or more keys have the same hash value), the hash function generates a new index for each key, which can lead to collisions.\n\nCollision resolution strategies aim to handle these conflicts efficiently. Some common strategies include:\n\n1. Separate chaining: Each bucket stores one entry, and when a collision occurs, it creates a separate linked list in memory for that bucket.\n\n2. Open addressing: In this strategy, all entries are stored in the same bucket, and when a collision occurs, the hash function returns a random index from the bucket.\n\n3. Linear probing: This method involves searching through the next available slot in the bucket until finding an empty slot or reaching the end of the bucket.\n\n4. Quadratic probing: Similar to linear probing but uses a different formula to find an empty slot.\n\n5. Double hashing: This technique uses a combination of the previous hash value and another constant value to generate a new hash value.\n\n6. Rolling hash: This method uses a rolling hash to distribute the load across multiple buckets.\n\nEach collision resolution strategy has its own trade-offs in terms of efficiency and performance, so choosing the right one depends on the specific requirements of the application. For example, if high availability and fault tolerance are critical, separate chaining might be the best choice. If simplicity and low overhead are important, open addressing could be the better option.",
